{"parse":{"title":"watermelon","pageid":54937,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|water melon}}\n==English==\n{{wp}}\n{{commons}}\n[[Image:Watermelons.jpg|thumb|right|Watermelons]]\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|en|🍉}} {{q|emoji}}\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom the 1610s, a compound of {{compound|en|water|melon}}. Compare {{cog|fr|melon d'eau}}, {{cog|de|Wassermelone}}, and {{cog|es|melón de agua}}.\n\nThe meanings referring to environmentalists and behind-schedule projects derive from the idea of having a [[green]] (eco-friendly, on-schedule) outward appearance while being [[red]] (socialist, behind schedule) in a hidden way comparable to that of the fruit.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈwɔːtəˌmɛlən/|a=RP}}\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈwɑtəɹˌmɛlən/|a=GA}}\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈwɒːt̞ɚˌmɛlən/|a=IE}}\n** {{IPA|en|/ˈwaːhɐˌmɛlən/|/ˈwaːʔɐˌmɛlən/|/ˈwaːʔɚˌmɛlən/|a=Dublin}}\n** {{IPA|en|/ˈwɔːɾɚˌmɛlən/|a=Ulster}}\n* {{audio|en|en-us-watermelon.ogg|a=US}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{wikidata lexeme|L208785}}\n{{en-noun|~}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|Q17507129}}A plant of the species {{taxfmt|Citrullus lanatus|species}}, bearing a [[melon]]-like fruit.\n# {{senseid|en|Q38645}}The fruit of the watermelon plant, having a green rind and watery flesh that is typically bright red when ripe and contains black [[seed]]s.\n# {{lb|en|pejorative|slang}} An [[environmentalist]] with [[socialist]] leanings, an [[ecosocialist]].\n#* {{quote-journal|en|author=Robin McKie|title=Merchants of Doubt by Naomi Oreskes and Erik M Conway|work=The Observer|date=2010-08-07|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2010/aug/08/merchants-of-doubt-oreskes-conway|issn=0029-7712|passage=According to this distorted view of life, environmentalists are '''watermelons''' – green on the outside, red on the inside – who want to impose regulation, “the slippery slope to socialism”, on the use of tobacco, ozone-destroying chemicals and greenhouse gases.}}\n# {{senseid|en|Q24820286}} A [[pinkish]]-red [[colour]], like that of watermelon flesh (also called watermelon pink).\n#: {{color panel|FDBCB4}}\n# A project that is [[present]]ed as on [[schedule]] when it actually has parts that are [[fall behind|falling behind]].\n#* {{quote-web|en|url=https://dzone.com/articles/watermelon-reporting|work=DZone|passage=The nuts and bolts of any project are transparency. If the project status is transparent, the '''watermelons''' can’t arise. If anybody is able to get the information, it will be difficult to hide something.|title='''Watermelon''' Reporting|date=2011-08-08|author=Marc Löffler|publisher=AnswerHub}}\n#* {{quote-web|en|url=https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/watch-out-watermelons-project-reports-ken-burrell|work=LinkedIn|passage=As a PMO [project management officer], wherever I see '''watermelon''' reporting, I encourage the PM [project manager] to be brave and honest enough to ask for help.|title=Watch out for '''watermelons''' in project reports|date=2015-09-17|author=Ken Burrell}}\n#* {{quote-web|en|url=https://www.cio.com/article/3617909/combatting-the-watermelon-effect-to-improve-digital-experience.html|work=CIO|passage=[see title]|title=Combatting the '''Watermelon''' Effect to Improve Digital Experience|date=2021-04-24|author=Sumir Karayi|publisher=IDG Communications|accessdate=5 June 2021|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20210605175839/https://www.cio.com/article/3617909/combatting-the-watermelon-effect-to-improve-digital-experience.html|archivedate=5 June 2021}}\n# {{lb|en|colloquial|slang}} A [[breast]], especially that of an [[adult]] or [[adolescent]] [[female]] [[human]].\n\n====Synonyms====\n* See [[Thesaurus:breasts]]\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col|en|watermelonade|watermelon beetle|watermelon tourmaline|watermelon radish|watermelonrita|watermelontini}}\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desc|mkj|wedmalan|bor=1}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{trans-top|plant}}\n* Afrikaans: {{t+|af|waatlemoen}}\n* Albanian: {{t+|sq|shalqi|m}}, {{t+|sq|bostan|m}}\n* Altai:\n*: Southern Altai: {{t|alt|арбуз}}\n* Arabic: {{t|ar|بَطِّيخ}} {{qualifier|collective}}, {{t|ar|بَطِّيخَة|f}} {{qualifier|singulative}}, {{t|ar|دَلَّاع|m}}, {{t+|ar|سندية|tr=sindiyya}}\n*: Algerian Arabic: {{t|arq|دلاع|tr=dillēʕ}}\n*: Chadian Arabic: {{t|shu|بطيخ|m|tr=bittēḵ}} {{qualifier|collective}}, {{t|shu|بطيخاي|f|tr=bittēḵāy}} {{qualifier|singulative}}\n*: Egyptian Arabic: {{t|arz|بطيخ|m|tr=baṭṭīḵ}} {{qualifier|collective}}, {{t|arz|بطيخة|f|tr=baṭṭīḵa}} {{qualifier|singulative}}\n*: Gulf Arabic: {{t|afb|جحّ|m|tr=jiḥḥ}}, {{t|afb|يح}}, {{t|afb|رقي|m|tr=raggī}}\n*: Hijazi Arabic: {{t|acw|بطيخ|m|tr=baṭṭīḵ}}, {{t|acw|حَبحَب|m|tr=ḥabḥab}}\n*: Mesopotamian Arabic: {{t|acm|رقّي|m|tr=raggi, raqqi}}, {{t|acm|شمزي|m|tr=šəmzi}}\n*: Moroccan Arabic: {{t|ary|دلاح|m|tr=dallāḥ}} {{qualifier|collective}}, {{t|ary|دلاحة|m|tr=dallāḥa}} {{qualifier|singulative}}\n*: North Levantine Arabic: {{t|apc|بطيخ|m|tr=baṭṭīḵ}}\n*: South Levantine Arabic: {{t|ajp|بطيخ|m|tr=baṭṭīḵ}}\n*: Tunisian Arabic: {{t|aeb|دلاع|m|tr=dillēʕ}}\n* Aramaic:\n*: Assyrian Neo-Aramaic: {{t|aii|ܫܸܦܬܝܼܵܐ|tr=šiptiya|m}}, {{t|aii|ܦܲܛܝܼܚܵܐ|tr=pāṭṭīḳa|m}}\n*: Classical Syriac: {{t|syc|ܦܲܛܝܼܚܵܐ|tr=paṭṭīḥā}}\n* Armenian: {{t+|hy|ձմերուկ}}\n* Aromanian: {{t|rup|peapine}}\n* Assamese: {{t|as|তৰমুজ গছ}}\n* Asturian: {{t+|ast|sandía|f}}\n* Azerbaijani: {{t+|az|qarpız}}\n* Bashkir: {{t|ba|ҡарбуз}}\n* Belarusian: {{t|be|каву́н|m}}\n* Bhojpuri: {{t|bho|तरबूजा}}\n* Bikol:\n*: Central Bikol: {{t|bcl|pakwan}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|ди́ня|f}}\n* Catalan: {{t|ca|sindriera|f}}\n* Cherokee: {{t|chr|ᎬᎩᏍᏗ}}\n* Cheyenne: {{t|chy|mȧhōō'o}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Cantonese: {{t+|yue|西瓜|tr=sai1 gwaa1}}\n*: Hokkien: {{t+|nan-hbl|西瓜|tr=si-koe}}, {{t|nan-hbl|生瓜|tr=siⁿ-koe}}\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|西瓜|tr=xīguā}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|lubenice|f}}, {{t+|cs|vodní meloun|m}}\n* Danish: {{t+|da|vandmelon|c}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|watermeloen|f}}\n* Esperanto: {{t|eo|akvomelono}}\n* Estonian: {{t+|et|arbuus}}, {{t|et|vesimelon}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|vesimeloni}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|pastèque|f}}, {{t+|fr|melon d'eau|m}}\